2. A concrete geometric ansatz for the capsule
Let’s pick a very explicit model to work with:
2.1 Split the 9D space
Write the geometric lane as a direct sum: [ W \cong V \oplus I,\quad \dim V = 4,\ \dim I = 5, ] where:
•	(V) will carry the effective Lorentzian structure (spacetime),
•	(I) will carry internal geometric directions (extra bulk geometry, graviton compass structure, etc.).
Choose coordinates:
•	(x^\mu) on (V), (\mu = 0,1,2,3),
•	(y^a) on (I), (a = 1,\dots,5).
2.2 Put a degenerate bilinear form on (W)
Define a bilinear form (B) on (W) by: [ B\big((x,y),(x,y)\big) \equiv \eta_{\mu\nu} x^\mu x^\nu, ] where (\eta = \mathrm{diag}(-1,1,1,1)) is the usual Minkowski metric on (V).
Key features:
•	(B) ignores the internal coordinates (y).
•	Any vector with (x=0) is automatically “null” under (B).
•	The null set in (W) is: [ \mathcal{N}_W = {(x,y) \in W \mid \eta(x,x) = 0}. ]
So the 4D light cone lifts to a thickened null cylinder in 9D: all internal directions over each null 4-vector.
2.3 Define the physical subgroup (G_{\text{phys}})
Now constrain (SO(9)):
Let [ G_{\text{phys}} \equiv { R \in SO(9) \mid B(Rw,Rw) = B(w,w)\ \forall w \in W }. ]
In words: the physical subgroup is the set of 9D rotations that preserve the degenerate form (B).
This has two immediate consequences:
•	On the 4D sector (V), the induced action must preserve (\eta) → it acts as an element of (SO(3,1)).
•	On the internal sector (I), it can act nontrivially as long as it doesn’t feed internal components into (B).
So you get a natural homomorphism: [ \Pi_{\text{geo}}: G_{\text{phys}} \to SO(3,1), ] given by “restrict (R) to (V) and read off its Lorentz part.”
The kernel of (\Pi_{\text{geo}}) are those (R) that:
•	act trivially on (V),
•	act nontrivially only on (I).
That’s exactly the “bulk-only” geometric freedom you’d expect.
